# Portal directory contract

**Doctrine:** ADR-0020. If this rule and `AGENTS.md` diverge, follow
`AGENTS.md` and fix this rule in the same change.

---

## Route boundary

`/{locale}/p/{portalSlug}` is the canonical portal boundary for org-owned
external or constrained audiences: employee, supplier, customer, investor, and
future portal audiences.

`/p` is externally reachable, but it is not anonymous public runtime. Portal
routes must be authenticated, invite-gated, or otherwise identity-bound.

### Route ownership

- `app/[locale]/p/[portalSlug]/layout.tsx` owns portal context resolution before
  rendering portal chrome.
- `/p/[portalSlug]` runtime files with dynamic params must use the Next.js App
  Router async params contract, for example
  `params: Promise<{ portalSlug: string }>` followed by `const { portalSlug } =
  await params`.
- `app/[locale]/p/**` owns routing, params, metadata, loading, error,
  not-found, and page composition only.
- `app/[locale]/p/**` must not contain ERP business logic, database query
  composition, authorization policy definitions, or mutation logic.
- Do not create `route.ts` files under `app/[locale]/p/**`. Portal HTTP
  contracts belong in the allowed `app/api/*` route-handler families documented
  by `AGENTS.md`.

---

## Portal shell

`components2/portal-shell/` owns portal chrome only:

- portal shell frame
- portal navigation composition
- portal identity/avatar affordances
- portal organization visibility
- portal loading/error chrome

It must not own:

- ERP business logic
- database reads or writes
- Server Actions
- HRM, supplier, customer, or investor domain policy

`/p` routes must not import or mount `AppShell` or `AppSubLayout` — the
canonical post-login app shell belongs to `/{locale}/o/{orgSlug}` only.
There is no `WorkbenchShell` / `WorkbenchSubLayout` — those names are
retired (ADR-0005); never reintroduce them.

---

## Portal control plane

`lib/portal/` owns portal infrastructure contracts:

- portal slug validation
- portal path helpers
- portal audience registry
- portal context types
- portal resolver contracts
- portal guard contracts
- portal-specific revalidation helpers

`lib/portal/` must not own ERP business logic. Audience business rules belong in
the relevant feature module, for example `lib/features/hrm/` for employee
self-service or a future supplier module for supplier workflows.

---

## Authorization

Portal Server Components and Server Actions must authorize independently. A
protected layout is not sufficient because Server Actions are separate entry
points. Portal-related route handlers are allowed only in the approved
`app/api/*` families and must perform their own portal authorization there.

Rules:

- Never trust `organizationId`, employee ID, supplier ID, customer ID, investor
  ID, or subject identity from `FormData`, JSON, query strings, or route params
  without server-side resolution.
- Resolve organization authority from `portalSlug` through the portal resolver.
- Use audience-specific guards for subject access once a portal audience ships.
- Do not call `requireOrgSession()` as the portal default guard; supplier,
  customer, investor, and some employee portal actors may not be Workbench org
  members.
- Keep `proxy.ts` as a locale/session cookie presence gate only.

---

## Path and naming

- Use `/p`, not `/t`, for portal routes.
- Path helpers must live under `lib/portal/`.
- Portal path helpers must emit locale-internal paths; callers add locale with
  `toLocalePath(locale, path)` when needed.
- Do not hard-code portal URLs in feature modules when a portal path helper
  exists.

---

## Forbidden

- `AppShell` or `AppSubLayout` imports under `app/[locale]/p/**` (post-login app shell is forbidden in portal routes; `WorkbenchShell` / `WorkbenchSubLayout` are retired names — never reintroduce, see ADR-0005).
- ERP business logic in `app/[locale]/p/**`, `components2/portal-shell/**`, or
  `lib/portal/**`.
- Portal auth decisions in `proxy.ts`.
- Anonymous public workflows under `/p`.
- Route-level organization hacks that bypass the portal resolver.
- Duplicate HRM, supplier, customer, or investor business logic for portal vs
  Workbench surfaces.
